A convolutional neural network model
With the first experiment (test_toolbox_deep_1.html), let's then add another convolution2dLayer as what Michael has done.
Layer = [imageInputLayer([28, 28, 1])
convolution2dLayer(5, 20, 'Stride', 1)
batchNormalizationLayer
reluLayer
maxPooling2dLayer(2, 'Stride', 2)
convolution2dLayer(5, 40, 'Stride', 1)
batchNormalizationLayer
reluLayer
maxPooling2dLayer(2, 'Stride', 2)
fullyConnectedLayer(100, 'WeightsInitializer', "he")
batchNormalizationLayer
reluLayer
fullyConnectedLayer(10, 'WeightsInitializer', "he")
batchNormalizationLayer
softmaxLayer
classificationLayer
];
You may have found out that I've added a "batchNormalizationLayer" in between the convolution2dLayer and activation (reluLayer). The batch normlization, or in short, batch norm, essentially helps with improving the train speed. Intuitively, you can think of this as what we usually do to normalize the input layer. We normalize the weighted inputs in each hidden layer. To understand why this helps and how to implement this in a deep NN, you may find it helpful to watch through the video Andrew Ng made (just simply search batch norm in Youtube).
Train options
options = trainingOptions('sgdm', 'MaxEpochs', 30, ...
'Shuffle', 'every-epoch', "MiniBatchSize", 200, ...
"ValidationData", {imgDataValid(:, :, :, :), labelsValid(:)}, ...
'ValidationFrequency', 500, ...
"InitialLearnRate", 0.03, ...
"LearnRateSchedule", "piecewise", ...
"LearnRateDropPeriod", 500, ...
'LearnRateDropFactor', 0.5, ...
'Momentum', 0, ...
"L2Regularization", 0.1, ...
"Plots", 'training-progress', ...
'Verbose', 0);
net = trainNetwork(imgDataTrain_(:, :, :, :), labelsTrain_(:), Layer, options);
Okay! Still encouraging this time although it doesn't appear to be a big jump--from 98.2% last time to 99% this try. Note all numbers reported were the first try I made. You may get different numbers, smaller or larger. It depends.
Something that worths a note. If you compare this one with what you've seen in test_toolbox_deep_1.html, you may be interested in the finding that test accuracy reached above ~95% after only 2 epochs while it took about 10 epochs in the model in test_toolbox_deep_1.html. That is how batch norm helps in the speeding the training process.
The last batch norm layer i added is actually kind of useless as what it all does is to normalize the weighted input before output activation. You can delete it anyway and try out again.
